Plot One - Relatively Constant Politcal Freedom¶

In the first two years of the trump and biden admins, we can see changing level of political freedom for nations in the world, on average. For the biden administration, indicators of political freedom are decreasing over his first two years in office. However this appears to be following an already existing trend and could potentially be influenced by various confounding variables. For the trump admin, levels of poltical freedom are increasing starting with him taking office. We see a signficant jump in right to assembly as well as right participate in goverment. While these are very promising indicators, there could be various confounding vars that would not allow us to see the full treatment effect.

Plot Two - Proportion Feeling Unsafe by Marginalized Group¶

Somewhat counterintuitvely we see the proportion of those feeling unhappy about the freedom from arrest, freedom of assembly, and freedom of political participation stays constant over a two year period of the trump admin, but increase exponentially during the final year of the biden admin. In praticular those who were part of the LGBTQ+ community, saw some of the greatest increases in dissatisfaction. This is intresting especially considering republican attacks on LGBTQ+ rights and the democrats relative support of such rights. Also intrestingly migrants felt a decrease in freedom of assembly over the first trump term, which makes sense considering his frequent attacks on migrants.

Plot Three - Changes in Markers for the United States¶

When you seperate our key indicators down to just the scores from the united states you can see a much more intuitive and pronounced impact of the presidency. Over the final two years of the trump admin you see a significant decrease in all measures of freedom and political rights. Outside of freedom for execution you see a significant drop in respect for each of these rights at the end of the trump admin. These all make a significant comeback at the start of the biden admin. However, following the sharp comeback, they begin to slip slightly across the board as we progress through the biden admin. However, all indicators remain elevated compared to where they lie at the end of the trump presidency.

Conclusions¶

In terms of the world. The american presidency does not seem to have a super obvious impact on poltical freedom around the world. Where we saw a decline in american political freedoms in the first trump term, the rest of the world experinced a significant increase in poltical freedom. Furthermore, in the biden admin throughout the world we saw a decrease in politcal freedom but an increase in america. It is also important to note throughout the world marginalized groups where signifcantly impacted realting to the decrease in freedoms we saw in 2021-2023. We can conclude that likley, there is confounding vars that are resposible for the world wide trends we see in political freedoms. However, within america, we can concldue there was a signifcant drop in political freedom due to the trump admin, and then a realtive increase following the election of Joe Biden.

Based on this plot, it seems as though the average civil rights over time is following a light cyclical pattern. All of the indicators increased at the start of the Trump presidency, remained relatively constant throughout the remainder of his term, and then decreased at the start of the Biden presidency. Unlike the Political Freedom analysis, however, the indicators remained very similar over time and did not see huge shifts throughout the period.

Analysis of Civil Rights Distribution¶

In [22]:
columns = df.columns[2:]
summary = df.groupby('year')[columns].agg(['median', 'std', 'min', 'max', lambda bottom_five: bottom_five.quantile(0.05), lambda top_95: top_95.quantile(0.95)])

metrics = ["median", "min", "max", "std"]

for metric in metrics:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

    for indicator in columns:
        label_clean = indicator.replace("_mean", "").upper()
        ax = plt.gca()
        ax.plot(
            summary.index, 
            summary[(indicator, metric)], 
            marker='o', 
            label=label_clean
        )

    plt.title(f'Civil Rights Indicators: {metric.upper()} Over Time')
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel(metric.capitalize())
    
    # Shade Trump (2017-2018) and Biden (2021-2022) start periods
    plt.axvspan(2017, 2019, color='orange', alpha=0.2, label='Trump Start')
    plt.axvspan(2021, 2023, color='blue', alpha=0.2, label='Biden Start')

    handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
    by_label = OrderedDict(zip(labels, handles))
    plt.legend(by_label.values(), by_label.keys(), title='Indicator', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')

    plt.grid(True)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Median: We notice that the trend for the median country is similar to the trend for the mean of the countries. However, the mean is greater than the median for all values, suggesting that a subset of the countries in the dataset are pulling the average values up. Furthermore, we notice that the median country experiences shifts more drastically than the global average would suggest. Ultimately, global civil rights protection worsened after 2020.

Min: The worst countries' scores dipped sharply between 2017–2019 (early Trump years) and recovered a bit during 2021–2023 (Biden start).

Max: The best countries reached peak scores around 2019–2020. Then slight declines in maximum scores in recent years (2021–2023). This demonstrates that even the best countries experienced worsened civil-rights after 2020.

Standard Deviation: We notice that the standard deviation of indicators was relatively uncorrelated in 2017-2019. However, after 2020, the standard deviation of indicators began to decrease in a highly correlated fashion. This suggests that the civil-rights for the countries in the dataset began to converge in 2020, representing a foundational shift in human rights which brought the world closer together

In [45]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

# Filter data up until 2017
df_pre_2017 = df_yearly_mean[df_yearly_mean.index <= 2017]

best_fit_lines = {}

for column in df_pre_2017.columns:
    data = df_pre_2017[[column]].dropna()
    
    if not data.empty:
        X = data.index.values.reshape(-1, 1)
        y = data[column].values
        
        model = LinearRegression()
        model.fit(X, y)
        
        best_fit_lines[column] = {
            'slope': model.coef_[0],
            'intercept': model.intercept_
        }

We have a lot of indicators, so we will separate the data into positive-trends and negative-trends for cleaner analysis.

Best Fit Lines¶

negative_slope = {key: value for key, value in best_fit_lines.items() if value['slope'] < 0}

# Filter data for post-2017
df_post_2017 = df_yearly_mean[df_yearly_mean.index > 2017]

def plot_trends(columns_dict, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    for i, column in enumerate(columns_dict.keys()):
        data = df_post_2017[[column]].dropna()
        if not data.empty:
            # Actual line
            plt.plot(data.index, data[column], label=f'{column} (Actual)', color=f'C{i}')
            
            # Best fit
            X = data.index.values.reshape(-1, 1)
            model = LinearRegression().fit(X, data[column].values)
            y_pred = model.predict(X)
            plt.plot(data.index, y_pred, linestyle='dotted', color=f'C{i}', label=f'{column} (Best Fit)')

    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Score')
    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Plot separately
plot_trends(positive_slope, "Post-2017 Indicators with Positive Trends")
plot_trends(negative_slope, "Post-2017 Indicators with Negative Trends")

The diference appears extremely small, however that could be due to errors or inconsistencies in scale. Let's standardize and calculate the difference between the predicted and actual values.

In [48]:
percent_diff_by_indicator = {}

for column in df_post_2017.columns:
    data = df_post_2017[[column]].dropna()
    if not data.empty:
        X = data.index.values.reshape(-1, 1)
        y_actual = data[column].values

        model = LinearRegression().fit(X, y_actual)
        y_pred = model.predict(X)

        y_pred_safe = y_pred.copy()
        y_pred_safe[y_pred_safe == 0] = 1e-6

        percent_diff = (y_actual - y_pred_safe) / y_pred_safe * 100
        percent_diff_by_indicator[column] = pd.Series(percent_diff, index=data.index)

df_percent_diff = pd.DataFrame(percent_diff_by_indicator)

# Plot
ax = df_percent_diff.plot(marker='o', figsize=(12, 6))
plt.title("Percentage Difference from Best-Fit Trend (Post-2017)")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Percent Difference (%)")
plt.axhline(0, color='black', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.7)
plt.legend(title="Indicator", bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc="upper left")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

From this analysis, we confirm that the majority of the economic prosperity indicators do not seem to be shifting relative to their historical trends. However, we should look at the standard deviation of these indicators to be certain that the administrations are not having significant impact.

However, we do note that the not-unemployed score and work score saw significant increase between 2018 and 2020. The quality of life score also saw significant increase post-2018.

Standard Dev¶

In [49]:
std_diff_by_indicator = {}

for column in df_post_2017.columns:
    data = df_post_2017[[column]].dropna()
    if not data.empty:
        X = data.index.values.reshape(-1, 1)
        y_actual = data[column].values

        model = LinearRegression().fit(X, y_actual)
        y_pred = model.predict(X)

        residuals = y_actual - y_pred
        std_resid = residuals.std(ddof=1) if residuals.std(ddof=1) != 0 else 1e-6

        std_dev_diff = residuals / std_resid
        std_diff_by_indicator[column] = pd.Series(std_dev_diff, index=data.index)

df_std_diff = pd.DataFrame(std_diff_by_indicator)

# Plot
ax = df_std_diff.plot(marker='o', figsize=(12, 6))
plt.title("Standard Deviation from Best-Fit Line (Post-2017)")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Deviation from Trend (Standard Deviations)")
plt.axhline(0, color='black', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.7)
plt.axhline(2, color='red', linestyle=':', linewidth=0.7)
plt.axhline(-2, color='red', linestyle=':', linewidth=0.7)
plt.legend(title="Indicator", bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc="upper left")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Aha! For almost every indicator and year, the deviation from the trend is within ±1 standard deviation. This suggests that the observed differences are small and likely due to random variation rather than meaningful departures from trend due to external factors.
